med a squeeze on consumer spending power as well as its near exclusion from the fast-growing online and convenience-store markets for a 5.6% fall in underlying sales in the six weeks to 5 January. The fall came despite a 1% boost to sales from a new move to open on Boxing Day and New Year's Day, according to analysts.</p><p>Dalton Philips, the chief executive, said the retailer had also been unable to compete with a blizzard of discount voucher programmes offered by rivals whose more up-to-date IT systems allowed them to target customers more effectively. His comments reflect the view of Sainsbury's, which said on Wednesday that promotional activity this Christmas \"was like no other\".</p><p>Meanwhile, Philips admitted that Morrisons had faced a competitive onslaught from discount stores such as Aldi and Lidl. He attributed about half of the supermarket's fall in underlying sales to customers opting to shop around at discounters rather than consolidating their spending in Morrisons, as they had done over previous Christmases.</p><p>\"People are being economically squeezed so they are not trading up and they are splitting their shopping basket among different stores,\" he said. \"They have been buying their confectionery from one store and their wine from another store this year. It's a big shift.\"</p><p>All the major supermarkets lost market share to discounters and upmarket rivals such as Waitrose in October and November. Official figures are not yet out for December, but only Sainsbury's has said it believes it fought off competition from these fast-growing specialists.</p><p>Philips said Morrisons had been particularly vulnerable to competition from the discounters because of its greater presence in the north of England and its position at the lower end of the market.</p><p>However, Philips said that, while the retailer was moving down prices on key items such as butter, milk and bread, it would not be changing its strategy to take on the likes of Aldi more directly.</p><p>\"We have got a very clear strategy of developing new channels in online and convenience and fundamentally that's where all the growth is. We believe quality and convenience will win through with consumers and that's where long term we will win.\"</p><p>He said that Morrisons was already working on \"antidotes\" to three of its major issues with an online service launching in Warwickshire on Friday, two convenience stores opening every week and a new loyalty programme allowing Morrisons to offer shoppers more targeted promotions that will begin trials in the next couple of months. But he admitted: \"In a very tough market our sales performance over Christmas was disappointing.\"</p>","headline":"Morrisons issues profit warning after shoppers opt for discount Christmas","trailText":"Supermarket blames consumer spending squeeze and near exclusion from online and convenience-store markets","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3yyj9","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/1/9/1389267966335/Morrisons-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/1/9/1389267966335/Morrisons-006.jpg","wordcount":"478","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"426657111","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8533955","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Sarah Butler","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-01-10T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2023497","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-01-12T11:54:02Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/jan/09/morrisons-profit-warning-discount-christmas-aldi-lidl","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/2014/jan/09/morrisons-profit-warning-discount-christmas-aldi-lidl","tags":[{"id":"business/morrisons","webTitle":"Morrisons","type":"keyword","sec