tly flavour of the month with health-conscious celebrities, were up 58% on last year, while spinach sales rose 13%, garlic 15% and Savoy cabbage 17%. Sushi sales were reported to be up 343%.</p><p>John Lewis also said that fashion, including its own branded clothes, had also performed well, with sales up 28% on last year.</p><p>Strong performance in the January sales confirms John Lewis as a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/jan/02/high-street-retailers-winners-and-losers\" title=\"\">Christmas winner</a>, alongside rival House of Fraser, in contrast to the lacklustre performance at Debenhams and falling clothing sales at Marks &amp; Spencer.</p><p>\"After getting off to a cracking start immediately after Christmas our clearance (sale) performance continued to be strong last week, resulting in an outstanding 23.6% on last year,\" Barry Matheson, director of retail services at John Lewis.</p><p>\"This was despite horrendous weather conditions throughout the whole of the New Year period which did nothing to deter customers shopping with clicks or in bricks.\" Waitrose reported this week its best ever Christmas, making a record £51m on 23 December, with 22,000 items going through its checkouts every minute.</p><p>IHS economist Howard Archer said John Lewis's figures were extremely impressive.</p><p>\"The performance highlighted John Lewis's position as one of the very top performers in the retailing sector. The John Lewis figures also highlighted the importance of having a strong online services as their online sales jumped 34.4% year-on-year in the week's trading.\"</p><p>\"It also indicated that squeezed consumers have been extremely keen to take advantage of genuine bargains in the clearance sales.\" Archer added.</p><p>JD Sports also reported on Friday that its Christmas sales were up more than 6% on last year citing \"robust performance\" from its shops. Chairman Peter Cowgill told BBC Radio 5 Live that JD Sports had not needed to cut their prices